2 <text font="0" height="19" left="221" textpieces="0" top="175" width="481">Socioscope: Spatio-Temporal Signal Recovery</text>
2 <text font="0" height="19" left="365" textpieces="0" top="202" width="194">from Social Media</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="219" textpieces="1" top="259" width="485">Jun-Ming Xu, Aniruddha Bhargava, Robert Nowak, and Xiaojin Zhu</text>
2 <text font="3" height="8" left="355" textpieces="0" top="288" width="212">Department of Computer Sciences</text>
2 <text font="3" height="8" left="299" textpieces="0" top="304" width="324">Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="282" textpieces="0" top="324" width="359">University of Wisconsin-Madison, Madison WI 53706, USA</text>
2 <text font="4" height="11" left="260" textpieces="0" top="341" width="402">xujm@cs.wisc.edu, aniruddha@wisc.edu, nowak@ece.wisc.edu,</text>
2 <text font="4" height="11" left="391" textpieces="0" top="358" width="141">jerryzhu@cs.wisc.edu</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="413" width="434">Abstract. Many real-world phenomena can be represented by a spatio-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="429" width="434">temporal signal: where, when, and how much. Social media is a tantaliz-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="446" width="434">ing data source for those who wish to monitor such signals. Unlike most</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="462" width="434">prior work, we assume that the target phenomenon is known and we are</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="479" width="434">given a method to count its occurrences in social media. However, count-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="495" width="434">ing is plagued by sample bias, incomplete data, and, paradoxically, data</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="512" width="434">scarcity  issues inadequately addressed by prior work. We formulate sig-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="528" width="434">nal recovery as a Poisson point process estimation problem. We explicitly</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="545" width="434">incorporate human population bias, time delays and spatial distortions,</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="561" width="434">and spatio-temporal regularization into the model to address the noisy</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="577" width="434">count issues. We present an ecient optimization algorithm and discuss</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="594" width="434">its theoretical properties. We show that our model is more accurate than</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="610" width="434">commonly-used baselines. Finally, we present a case study on wildlife</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="627" width="434">roadkill monitoring, where our model produces qualitatively convincing</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="245" textpieces="0" top="643" width="43">results.</text>
2 <text font="5" height="16" left="202" textpieces="1" top="689" width="141">1  Introduction</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="725" width="519">Many real-world phenomena of interest to science are spatio-temporal in nature.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="16" left="202" textpieces="1" top="743" width="519">They can be characterized by a real-valued intensity function f  R0, where</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="761" width="519">the value fs,tquanties the prevalence of the phenomenon at location s and time</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="779" width="519">t. Examples include wildlife mortality, algal blooms, hail damage, and seismic</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="796" width="519">intensity. Direct instrumental sensing of f is often dicult and expensive. So-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="814" width="519">cial media oers a unique sensing opportunity for such spatio-temporal signals,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="832" width="519">where users serve the role of sensors by posting their experiences of a target</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="850" width="519">phenomenon. For instance, social media users readily post their encounters with</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="868" width="475">dead animals: I saw a dead crow on its back in the middle of the road.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="886" width="496">There are at least three challenges faced when using human social media</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="904" width="106">users as sensors:</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="208" textpieces="0" top="932" width="512">1. Social media sources are not always reliable and consistent, due to factors</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="228" textpieces="0" top="950" width="493">including the vagaries of language and the psychology of users. This makes</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="228" textpieces="0" top="968" width="493">identifying topics of interest and labeling social media posts extremely chal-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="228" textpieces="0" top="986" width="51">lenging.</text>
=============================== PAGE ===================================
=============================== COL ===================================
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="202" textpieces="1" top="142" width="328">2       Xu, J., Bhargava, A., Nowak, R., and Zhu, X.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="208" textpieces="0" top="180" width="512">2. Social media users are not under our control. In most cases, users cannot be</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="228" textpieces="0" top="198" width="493">directed or focused or maneuvered as we wish. The distribution of human</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="228" textpieces="0" top="216" width="493">users (our sensors) depends on many factors unrelated to the sensing task</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="228" textpieces="0" top="234" width="55">at hand.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="208" textpieces="0" top="252" width="512">3. Location and time stamps associated with social media posts may be er-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="228" textpieces="0" top="270" width="493">roneous or missing. Most posts do not include GPS coordinates, and self-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="228" textpieces="0" top="288" width="493">reported locations can be inaccurate or false. Furthermore, there can be</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="228" textpieces="0" top="306" width="493">random delays between an event of interest and the time of the social media</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="228" textpieces="0" top="324" width="165">post related to the event.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="355" width="519">Most prior work in social media event analysis has focused on the rst challenge.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="373" width="519">Sophisticated natural language processing techniques have been used to identify</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="391" width="519">social media posts relevant to a topic of interest [21, 2, 16] and advanced machine</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="409" width="519">learning tools have been proposed to discover popular or emerging topics in social</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="427" width="440">media [1, 12, 22]. We discuss the related work in detail in Section 3.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="445" width="496">Our work in this paper focuses on the latter two challenges. We are interested</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="463" width="519">in a specic topic or target phenomenon of interest that is given and xed be-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="481" width="519">forehand, and we assume that we are also given a (perhaps imperfect) method,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="499" width="519">such as a trained text classier, to identify target posts. The rst challenge is</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="517" width="519">relevant here, but is not the focus of our work. The main concerns of this paper</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="535" width="519">are to deal with the highly non-uniform distribution of human users (sensors),</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="553" width="519">which profoundly aects our capabilities for sensing natural phenomena such as</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="571" width="519">wildlife mortality, and to cope with the uncertainties in the location and time</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="589" width="519">stamps associated with related social media posts. The main contribution of the</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="607" width="519">paper is robust methodology for deriving accurate spatiotemporal maps of the</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="625" width="336">target phenomenon in light of these two challenges.</text>
2 <text font="5" height="16" left="202" textpieces="1" top="673" width="166">2  The Socioscope</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="713" width="519">We propose Socioscope, a probabilistic model that robustly recovers spatiotem-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="731" width="519">poral signals from social media data. Formally, consider f dened on discrete</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="749" width="519">spatiotemporal bins. For example, a bin (s, t) could be a U.S. state s on day t,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="767" width="518">or a county s in hour t. From the rst stage we obtain xs,t, the count of tar-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="785" width="518">get social media posts within that bin. The task is to estimate fs,t from xs,t.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="806" width="519">A commonly-used estimate is fs,t = xs,t itself. This estimate can be justied</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="824" width="519">as the maximum likelihood estimate of a Poisson model x  Poisson(f ). This</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="842" width="519">idea underlines several emerging systems such as earthquake damage monitoring</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="859" width="518">from Twitter [8]. However, this estimate is unsatisfactory since the counts xs,t</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="877" width="519">can be noisy: as mentioned before, the estimate ignores population bias  more</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="895" width="519">target posts are generated when and where there are more social media users; the</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="913" width="519">location of a target post is frequently inaccurate or missing, making it dicult</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="931" width="519">to assign to the correct bin; and target posts can be quite sparse even though</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="949" width="489">the total volume of social media is huge. Socioscope addresses these issues.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="968" width="496">For notational simplicity, we often denote our signal of interest by a vector</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="986" width="147">f = (f1, . . . , fn)   Rn</text>
2 <text font="2" height="10" left="342" textpieces="0" top="992" width="77">0, where fj</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="425" textpieces="0" top="986" width="296">is a non-negative target phenomenon intensity</text>
