=============================== COL ===================================
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="282" textpieces="1" top="142" width="439">Socioscope: Spatio-Temporal Signal Recovery from Social Media       3</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="180" width="519">in source bin j = 1 . . . n. We will use a wildlife example throughout the section.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="198" width="519">In this example, a source bin is a spatiotemporal unit such as California, day</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="216" width="518">1, and fjis the squirrel activity level in that unit. The mapping between index</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="234" width="478">j and the aforementioned (s, t) is one-one and will be clear from context.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="279" width="306">2.1  Correcting Human Population Bias</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="310" width="519">For now, assume each target post comes with precise location and time meta</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="328" width="518">data. This allows us to count xj, the number of target posts in bin j. Given xj,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="349" width="519">it is tempting to use the maximum likelihood estimate fj= xj which assumes a</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="367" width="519">simple Poisson model xj Poisson(fj). However, this model is too naive: Even</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="385" width="517">if fj = fk, e.g., the level of squirrel activities is the same in two bins, we would</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="403" width="519">expect xj &gt; xk if there are more people in bin j than in bin k, simply because</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="421" width="290">more people see the same group of squirrels.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="439" width="496">To account for this population bias, we dene an active social media user</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="457" width="544">population intensity (loosely called human population below) g = (g1, . . . , gn)  </text>
2 <text font="1" height="12" left="202" textpieces="2" top="478" width="519">Rn 0. Let zj be the count of all social media posts in bin j, the vast majority of</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="492" width="518">which are not about the target phenomenon. We assume zj  Poisson(gj). Since</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="3" top="510" width="476">typically zj    0, the maximum likelihood estimate gj= zj is reasonable.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="529" width="299">Importantly, we then posit the Poisson model</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="385" textpieces="3" top="562" width="336">xj Poisson((fj, gj)).                           (1)</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="595" width="518">The intensity is dened by a link function (fj, gj). In this paper, we simply</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="3" top="613" width="519">dene (fj, gj) = fj  gj but note that other more sophisticated link functions</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="631" width="519">can be learned from data. Given xj and zj, one can then easily estimate fj with</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="651" width="204">the plug-in estimator fj = xj/z</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="408" textpieces="0" top="657" width="9">j.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="697" width="321">2.2  Handling Noisy and Incomplete Data</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="728" width="519">This would have been the end of the story if we could reliably assign each post</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="746" width="519">to a source bin. Unfortunately, this is often not the case for social media. In this</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="764" width="519">paper, we focus on the problem of spatial uncertainty due to noisy or incomplete</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="782" width="519">social media data. A prime example of spatial uncertainty is the lack of location</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="800" width="519">meta data in posts from Twitter (called tweets).1 In recent data we collected,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="818" width="519">only 3% of tweets contain the latitude and longitude at which they were created.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="836" width="519">Another 47% contain a valid user self-declared location in his or her prole (e.g.,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="854" width="519">New York, NY). However, such location does not automatically change while</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="872" width="519">the user travels and thus may not be the true location at which a tweet is posted.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="890" width="519">The remaining 50% do not contain location at all. Clearly, we cannot reliably</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="908" width="456">assign the latter two kinds of tweets to a spatiotemporal source bin.2</text>
2 <text font="3" height="8" left="206" textpieces="1" top="935" width="515">1  It may be possible to recover occasional location information from the tweet text</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="217" textpieces="0" top="954" width="358">itself instead of the meta data, but the problem still exists.</text>
2 <text font="3" height="8" left="206" textpieces="1" top="968" width="515">2  Another kind of spatiotemporal uncertainty exists in social media even when the local</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="217" textpieces="0" top="987" width="504">and time meta data of every post is known: social media users may not immediately</text>
