2 <text font="4" height="12" left="202" textpieces="1" top="142" width="328">4       Xu, J., Bhargava, A., Nowak, R., and Zhu, X.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="180" width="496">To address this issue, we borrow an idea from Positron Emission Tomogra-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="198" width="519">phy [19]. In particular, we dene m detector bins which are conceptually distinct</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="216" width="519">from the n source bins. The idea is that an event originating in some source bin</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="234" width="519">goes through a transition process and ends up in one of the detector bins, where</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="252" width="515">it is detected. This transition is modeled by an m  n matrix P = {Pij} where</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="362" textpieces="2" top="289" width="359">Pij= Pr(detector i | source j).                       (2)</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="327" width="151">P is column stochastic:</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="374" textpieces="0" top="322" width="11">m</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="374" textpieces="0" top="334" width="19">i=1</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="396" textpieces="1" top="327" width="324">Pij= 1, j. We defer the discussion of our specic</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="345" width="519">P to a case study, but we mention that it is possible to reliably estimate P</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="362" width="519">directly from social media data (more on this later). Recall the target post</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="380" width="518">intensity at source bin j is (fj, gj). We use the transition matrix to dene the</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="398" width="518">target post intensity hi (note that hi can itself be viewed as a link function</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="203" textpieces="1" top="416" width="163"> (f , g)) at detector bin i:</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="394" textpieces="1" top="466" width="30">hi=</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="435" textpieces="0" top="450" width="7">n</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="428" textpieces="0" top="486" width="21">j=1</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="452" textpieces="2" top="466" width="269">Pij(fj, gj).                             (3)</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="521" width="496">For the spatial uncertainty that we consider, we create three kinds of detector</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="539" width="519">bins. For a source bin j such as California, day 1, the rst kind collects target</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="557" width="519">posts on day 1 whose latitude and longitude meta data is in California. The</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="574" width="519">second kind collects target posts on day 1 without latitude and longitude meta</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="592" width="519">data, but whose user self-declared prole location is in California. The third kind</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="610" width="519">collects target posts on day 1 without any location information. Note the third</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="628" width="519">kind of detector bin is shared by all other source bins for day 1, such as Nevada,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="646" width="519">day 1, too. Consequently, if we had n = 50T source bins corresponding to the</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="664" width="491">50 US states over T days, there would be m = (2  50 + 1)T detector bins.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="684" width="496">Critically, our observed target counts x are now with respect to the m de-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="702" width="518">tector bins instead of the n source bins: x = (x1, . . . , xm) . We will also denote</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="720" width="518">the count sub-vector for the rst kind of detector bins by x(1), the second kind</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="738" width="518">x(2), and the third kind x(3). The same is true for the overall counts z. A trivial</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="756" width="480">approach is to only utilize x(1) and z(1)to arrive at the plug-in estimator</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="415" textpieces="1" top="796" width="57">fj = x(1)</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="457" textpieces="0" top="803" width="5">j</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="473" textpieces="0" top="796" width="29">/z(1)</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="487" textpieces="0" top="803" width="5">j</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="504" textpieces="1" top="796" width="217">.                                (4)</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="833" width="519">As we will show, we can obtain a better estimator by incorporating noisy data</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="851" width="519">x(2) and incomplete data x(3). z(1) is suciently large and we will simply ignore</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="869" width="85">z(2) and z(3).</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="217" textpieces="0" top="904" width="504">post right at the spot where a target phenomenon happens. Instead, there usually</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="217" textpieces="0" top="921" width="504">is an unknown time delay and spatial shift between the phenomenon and the post</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="217" textpieces="0" top="937" width="504">generation. For example, one may not post a squirrel encounter on the road until she</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="217" textpieces="0" top="954" width="504">arrives at home later; the local and time meta data only reects tweet-generation</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="217" textpieces="0" top="970" width="504">at home. This type of spatiotemporal uncertainty can be addressed by the same</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="217" textpieces="0" top="987" width="200">source-detector transition model.</text>
=============================== PAGE ===================================
