2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="479" width="519">smooth, i.e., neighboring source bins in space or time tend to have similar</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="497" width="519">intensity. We therefore adopt a penalized likelihood approach by constructing a</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="515" width="519">graph-based regularizer. The undirected graph is constructed so that the nodes</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="533" width="519">are the source bins. Let W be the n  n symmetric non-negative weight matrix.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="551" width="519">The edge weights are such that Wjkis large if j and k correspond to neighboring</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="569" width="519">bins in space and time. Since W is domain specic, we defer its construction to</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="587" width="96">the case study.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="606" width="496">Before discussing the regularizer, we need to perform a change of variables.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="624" width="519">Poisson intensity f is non-negative, necessitating a constrained optimization</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="642" width="519">problem. It is more convenient to work with an unconstrained problem. To this</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="660" width="519">end, we work with the exponential family natural parameters of Poisson. Specif-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="678" width="59">ically, let</text>
