2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="180" width="138">2.4  Optimization</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="207" width="519">We solve the Socioscope optimization problem (9) with BFGS, a quasi-Newton</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="225" width="347">method [14]. The gradient can be easily computed as</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="398" textpieces="1" top="255" width="323">= L  HP (r  1),                         (10)</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="3" top="285" width="519">where r = (r1. . . rm) is a ratio vector with ri = xi/hi, and H is a diagonal</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="303" width="187">matrix with Hjj= (j, j).</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="320" width="496">We initialize  with the following heuristic. Given counts x and the transition</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="338" width="518">matrix P , we compute the least-squared projection 0 to x  P0 2. This pro-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="356" width="519">jection is easy to compute. However, 0 may contain negative components not</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="374" width="518">suitable for Poisson intensity. We force positivity by setting 0 max(104, 0)</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="392" width="519">element-wise, where the oor 104 ensures that log 0 &gt; . From the deni-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="410" width="412">tion (, ) = exp( + ), we then obtain the initial parameter</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="410" textpieces="3" top="440" width="311">0= log 0 .                              (11)</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="470" width="496">Our optimization is ecient: problems with more than one thousand variables</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="487" width="401">(n) are solved in about 15 seconds with fminunc() in Matlab.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="530" width="176">2.5  Parameter Tuning</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="557" width="519">The choice of the regularization parameter  has a profound eect on the smooth-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="575" width="519">ness of the estimates. It may be possible to select these parameters based on prior</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="593" width="519">knowledge in certain problems, but for our experiments we select these param-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="611" width="519">eters using a cross-validation (CV) procedure, which gives us a fully data-based</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="629" width="269">and objective approach to regularization.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="647" width="496">CV is quite simple to implement in the Poisson setting. A hold-out set of data</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="665" width="519">can be constructed by simply sub-sampling events from the total observation</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="683" width="519">uniformly at random. This produces a partial data set of a subset of the counts</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="701" width="519">that follows precisely the same distribution as the whole set, modulo a decrease</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="719" width="519">in the total intensity per the level of subsampling. The complement of the hold-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="736" width="519">out set is what remains of the full dataset, and we will call this the training set.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="754" width="519">The hold-out set is taken to be a specic fraction of the total. For theoretical</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="772" width="519">reasons beyond the scope of this paper, we do not recommend leave-one-out</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="790" width="69">CV [18, 6].</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="808" width="496">CV is implemented by generating a number of random splits of this type (we</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="826" width="519">can generate as many as we wish), and for each split we run the optimization</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="844" width="519">algorithm above on the training set for a range of values of . Then compute the</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="862" width="519">(unregularized) value of the log-likelihood on the hold-out set. This provides us</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="880" width="519">with an estimate of the log-likelihood for each setting of . We simply select the</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="898" width="339">setting that maximizes the estimated log-likelihood.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="940" width="241">2.6  Theoretical Considerations</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="968" width="519">The natural measure of signal-to-noise in this problem is the number of counts in</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="986" width="519">each bin. The higher the counts, the more stable and less noisy our estimators</text>
