=============================== COL ===================================
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="282" textpieces="1" top="142" width="439">Socioscope: Spatio-Temporal Signal Recovery from Social Media       7</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="180" width="517">will be. Indeed, if we directly observe xi Poisson(hi), then the normalized error</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="198" width="54">E[(xihi</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="236" textpieces="0" top="206" width="11">hi</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="260" textpieces="0" top="198" width="60">)2] = h1</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="305" textpieces="0" top="205" width="4">i</text>
2 <text font="1" height="14" left="325" textpieces="0" top="197" width="39"> x1</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="349" textpieces="0" top="205" width="4">i</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="365" textpieces="0" top="198" width="356">. So larger counts, due to larger underlying intensities,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="216" width="519">lead to small errors on a relative scale. However, the accuracy of our recovery</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="234" width="519">also depends on the regularity of the underlying function f . If it is very smooth,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="252" width="519">for example a constant function, then the error would be inversely proportional</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="269" width="519">to the total number of counts, not the number in each individual bin. This is</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="287" width="485">because in the extreme smooth case, f is determined by a single constant.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="305" width="496">To give some insight into dependence of the estimate on the total number of</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="323" width="519">counts, suppose that f is the underlying continuous intensity function of interest.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="341" width="519">Furthermore, let f be a H older -smooth function. The parameter  is related</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="359" width="519">to the number of continuous derivatives f has. Larger values of  correspond</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="377" width="519">to smoother functions. Such a model is reasonable for the application at hand,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="395" width="519">as discussed in our motivation for regularization above. We recall the following</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="413" width="411">minimax lower bound, which follows from the results in [7, 20].</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="441" width="519">Theorem 1. Let f be a H older -smooth d-dimensional intensity function and</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="459" width="519">suppose we observe N events from the distribution Poisson(f ). Then there exists</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="477" width="184">a constant C&gt; 0 such that</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="347" textpieces="0" top="520" width="17">inf</text>
2 <text font="2" height="5" left="355" textpieces="1" top="539" width="4">b  f</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="368" textpieces="0" top="520" width="23">sup</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="375" textpieces="0" top="535" width="6">f</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="394" textpieces="1" top="509" width="73">E[ f  f 2</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="461" textpieces="0" top="516" width="10">1]</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="425" textpieces="1" top="530" width="23">f 2</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="442" textpieces="0" top="537" width="6">1</text>
2 <text font="1" height="14" left="483" textpieces="0" top="519" width="52"> CN</text>
2 <text font="6" height="7" left="541" textpieces="0" top="513" width="20">2</text>
2 <text font="6" height="7" left="539" textpieces="1" top="522" width="37">2+d   ,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="562" width="519">where the inmum is over all possible estimators. The error is measured with the</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="580" width="519">1-norm, rather than two norm, which is a more appropriate and natural norm</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="598" width="519">in density and intensity estimation. The theorem tells us that no estimator can</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="616" width="519">achieve a faster rate of error decay than the bound above. There exist many</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="634" width="519">types of estimators that nearly achieve this bound (e.g., to within a log factor),</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="652" width="519">and with more work it is possible to show that our regularized estimators, with</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="670" width="519">adaptively chosen bin sizes and appropriate regularization parameter settings,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="688" width="519">could also nearly achieve this rate. For the purposes of this discussion, the lower</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="706" width="388">bound, which certainly applies to our situation, will suce.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="724" width="496">For example, consider just two spatial dimensions (d = 2) and  = 1 which</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="741" width="519">corresponds to Lipschitz smooth functions, a very mild regularity assumption.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="759" width="519">Then the bound says that the error is proportional to N1/2. This gives useful</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="777" width="519">insight into the minimal data requirements of our methods. It tells us, for exam-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="795" width="519">ple, that if we want to reduce the error of the estimator by a factor of say 2, then</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="813" width="519">the total number of counts must be increased by a factor of 4. If the smoothness</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="831" width="519"> is very large, then doubling the counts can halve the error. The message is</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="849" width="500">simple. More events and higher counts will provide more accurate estimates.</text>
2 <text font="5" height="16" left="202" textpieces="1" top="894" width="153">3  Related Work</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="932" width="519">To our knowledge, there is no comparable prior work that focuses on robust</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="950" width="519">single recovery from social media (i.e., the second stage as we mentioned in</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="968" width="519">the introduction). However, there has been considerable related work on the rst</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="986" width="224">stage, which we summarize below.</text>
