2 <text font="4" height="12" left="202" textpieces="1" top="142" width="328">8       Xu, J., Bhargava, A., Nowak, R., and Zhu, X.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="180" width="496">Topic detection and tracking (TDT) aims at identifying emerging topics from</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="198" width="519">text stream and grouping documents based on their topics. The early work in</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="216" width="519">this direction began with news text streamed from newswire and transcribed</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="234" width="519">from other media [1]. Recent research focused on user-generated content on</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="252" width="519">the web and on the spatio-temporal variation of topics. Latent Dirichlet Al-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="269" width="519">location (LDA) [3] is a popular unsupervised method to detect topics. Mei</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="287" width="519">et al. [12] extended LDA by taking spatio-temporal context into account to iden-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="305" width="519">tify subtopics from weblogs. They analyzed the spatio-temporal pattern of topic</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="323" width="519"> by Pr(time|, location) and Pr(location|, time), and showed that documents</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="341" width="519">created from the same spatio-temporal context tend to share topics. In the same</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="359" width="519">spirit, Yin et al. [22] studied GPS-associated documents, whose coordinates are</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="377" width="519">generated by Gaussian Mixture Model in their generative framework. Cataldi</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="395" width="519">et al. [4] proposed a feature-pivot method. They rst identied keywords whose</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="413" width="519">occurrences dramatically increase in a specied time interval and then connected</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="431" width="519">the keywords to detect emerging topics. Besides text, social network structure</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="449" width="519">also provides important information for detecting community-based topics and</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="467" width="90">user interests.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="486" width="496">Event detection is highly related to TDT. Yang et al. [21] uses clustering</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="504" width="519">algorithm to identify events from news streams. Others tried to distinguish posts</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="522" width="519">related to real world events from posts about non-events, such as describing</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="540" width="519">daily life or emotions [2]. Real world events were also detected in Flickr photos</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="558" width="519">with meta information and Twitter. Other researchers were interested in events</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="576" width="519">with special characteristics, such as controversial events and local events. Sakaki</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="594" width="519">et al. [16] monitored Twitter to detect real-time events such as earthquakes and</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="612" width="71">hurricanes.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="632" width="496">Another line of related work uses social media as a data source to answer</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="650" width="519">scientic questions [11]. Most previous work studied questions in linguistic, so-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="667" width="519">ciology and human interactions. For example, Eisenstein et al. [9] studied the</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="685" width="519">geographic linguistic variation with geotagged social media. Gupte et al. [10]</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="703" width="435">studied social hierarchy and stratication in online social network.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="723" width="496">As stated earlier, Socioscope diers from past work in its focus on robust</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="741" width="519">signal recovery on predened target phenomena. The target posts may be gen-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="759" width="519">erated at a very low, though sustained, rate, and are corrupted by noise. The</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="777" width="509">above approaches are unlikely to estimate the underlying intensity accurately.</text>
2 <text font="5" height="16" left="202" textpieces="1" top="831" width="245">4  A Synthetic Experiment</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="878" width="519">We start with a synthetic experiment whose known ground-truth intensity f al-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="896" width="519">lows us to quantitatively evaluate the eectiveness of Socioscope. The synthetic</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="914" width="519">experiment matches the case study in the next section. There are 48 US con-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="932" width="519">tinental states plus Washington DC, and T = 24 hours. This leads to a total</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="950" width="519">of n = 1176 source bins, and m = (2  49 + 1)T = 2376 detector bins. The</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="968" width="519">transition matrix P is the same as in the case study, to be discussed later. The</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="986" width="447">overall counts z are obtained from actual Twitter data and g = z(1).</text>
