2 <text font="1" height="13" left="342" textpieces="1" top="580" width="379">gs,t and show the daily curve in Figure 2(c). From these</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="598" width="519">two plots, we clearly see that human population intensity varies greatly both</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="616" width="163">spatially and temporally.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="662" width="519">Identifying Target Posts to Obtain Counts x. To produce the target counts</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="680" width="519">x, we need to rst identify target posts describing roadkill events. Although not</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="698" width="500">part of Socioscope, we detail this preprocessing step here for reproducibility.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="716" width="496">In step 1, we collected tweets using a keyword API. Each tweet must contain</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="734" width="519">the wildlife name (e.g., squirrel(s)) and the phrase ran over. We obtained</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="752" width="519">5857 squirrel tweets, 325 chipmunk tweets, 180 opossum tweets and 159 armadillo</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="770" width="519">tweets during the study period. However, many such tweets did not actually</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="788" width="519">describe roadkill events. For example, I almost ran over an armadillo on my</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="806" width="519">longboard, luckily my cat-like reexes saved me. Clearly, the author did not kill</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="824" width="91">the armadillo.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="842" width="496">In step 2, we built a binary text classier to identify target posts among them.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="860" width="519">Following [17], the tweets were case-folded without any stemming or stopword</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="878" width="519">removal. Any user mentions preceded by a @ were replaced by the anonymized</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="896" width="519">user name @USERNAME. Any URLs staring with http were replaced by</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="914" width="519">the token HTTPLINK. Hashtags (compound words following #) were not</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="932" width="519">split and were treated as a single token. Emoticons, such as :) or :D, were</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="950" width="519">also included as tokens. Each tweet is then represented by a feature vector con-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="968" width="519">sisting of unigram and bigram counts. If any unigram or bigram included animal</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="986" width="519">names, we added an additional feature by replacing the animal name with the</text>
=============================== PAGE ===================================
=============================== COL ===================================
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="202" textpieces="1" top="142" width="328">12      Xu, J., Bhargava, A., Nowak, R., and Zhu, X.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="180" width="519">generic token ANIMAL. For example, we would created an extra feature over</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="198" width="519">ANIMAL for the bigram over raccoon. The training data consists of 1,450</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="216" width="519">manually labeled tweets in August 2011 (i.e., outside our study period). These</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="234" width="519">training tweets contain hundreds of animal species, not just the target species.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="252" width="519">The binary label is whether the tweet is a true rst-hand roadkill experience.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="269" width="519">We trained a linear Support Vector Machine (SVM). The CV accuracy is nearly</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="287" width="519">90%. We then applied this SVM to classify tweets surviving step 1. Those tweets</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="305" width="353">receiving a positive label were treated as target posts.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="1" top="324" width="496">In step 3, we produce x(1), x(2), x(3) counts. Because these target tweets were</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="342" width="519">collected by the keyword API, the nature of the Twitter API means that most</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="360" width="519">do not contain precise location information. As mentioned earlier, only 3% of</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="378" width="519">them contain coordinates. We processed this 3% by the same reverse geocoding</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="398" width="452">database to map them to a US state s, and place them in the x(1)</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="639" textpieces="0" top="405" width="14">s,t</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="661" textpieces="0" top="398" width="60">detection</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="416" width="519">bins. 47% of the target posts do not contain coordinates but can be mapped to</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="436" width="518">a US state from user self-declared prole location. These are placed in the x(2)</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="705" textpieces="0" top="443" width="14">s,t</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="454" width="519">detection bins. The remaining 50% contained no location meta data, and were</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="474" width="113">placed in the x(3)</text>
2 <text font="2" height="9" left="300" textpieces="0" top="481" width="5">t</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="321" textpieces="1" top="474" width="107">detection bins.3</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="524" width="519">Constructing the Transition Matrix P. In this study, P characterizes the</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="541" width="519">fraction of tweets which were actually generated in source bin (s, t) end up in</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="559" width="519">the three detector bins: precise location st(1), potentially noisy location st(2),</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="577" width="321">and missing location t(3). We dene P as follows:</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="2" top="596" width="496">P(s,t)(1),(s,t) = 0.03, and P(r,t)(1),(s,t) = 0 for r = s to reect the fact that</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="616" width="333">we know precisely 3% of the target posts location.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="2" top="635" width="496">P(r,t)(2),(s,t)= 0.47Mr,s for all r, s. M is a 49  49 mis-self-declare matrix.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="653" width="519">Mr,s is the probability that a user self-declares in her prole that she is in state r,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="671" width="519">but her post is in fact generated in state s. We estimated M from a separate large</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="689" width="519">set of tweets with both coordinates and self-declared prole locations. The M</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="707" width="519">matrix is asymmetric and interesting in its own right: many posts self-declared</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="725" width="519">in California or New York were actually produced all over the country; many</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="743" width="519">self-declared in Washington DC were actually produced in Maryland or Virgina;</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="761" width="519">more posts self-declare Wisconsin but were actually in Illinois than the other</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="778" width="80">way around.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="1" top="797" width="496">Pt(3),(s,t) = 0.50. This aggregates tweets with missing information into the</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="815" width="177">third kind of detector bins.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="865" width="519">Specifying the Graph Regularizer. Our graph has two kinds of edges. Tem-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="883" width="519">poral edges connect source bins with the same state and adjacent hours by weight</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="901" width="519">wt. Spatial edges connect source bins with the same hour and adjacent states by</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="919" width="519">weight ws. The regularization weight  was absorbed into wtand ws. We tuned</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="3" top="937" width="471">the weights wtand wswith CV on the 2D grid {103, 102.5, . . . , 103}2.</text>
2 <text font="3" height="8" left="206" textpieces="1" top="968" width="515">3  There were actually only a fraction of all tweets without location which came from</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="217" textpieces="0" top="987" width="393">all over the world. We estimated this US/World fraction using z.</text>
=============================== PAGE ===================================
=============================== COL ===================================
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="282" textpieces="1" top="142" width="439">Socioscope: Spatio-Temporal Signal Recovery from Social Media      13</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="1" top="180" width="94">5.2  Results</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="206" width="519">We present results on four animals: armadillos, chipmunks, squirrels, opossums.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="224" width="519">Perhaps surprisingly, precise roadkill intensities for these animals are apparently</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="242" width="519">unknown to science (This serves as a good example of the value Socioscope may</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="260" width="519">provide to wildlife scientists). Instead, domain experts were only able to provide</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="278" width="519">a range map of each animal, see the left column in Figure 3. These maps indicate</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="296" width="519">presence/absence only, and were extracted from NatureServe [15]. In addition,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="314" width="519">the experts dened armadillo and opossum as nocturnal, chipmunk as diurnal,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="331" width="519">and squirrels as both crepuscular (active primarily during twilight) and diurnal.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="349" width="519">Due to the lack of quantitative ground-truth, our comparison will necessarily be</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="367" width="138">qualitative in nature.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="385" width="496">Socioscope provides sensible estimates on these animals. For example, Fig-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="403" width="519">ure 4(a) shows counts x(1)+ x(2)for chipmunks which is very sparse (the largest</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="423" width="519">count in any bin is 3), and Figure 4(b) the Socioscope estimate f . The axes are</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="441" width="519">the same as in Figure 2(a). In addition, we present the state-by-state intensity</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="461" width="519">maps in the middle column of Figure 3 by aggregating f spatially. The Socio-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="479" width="519">scope results match the range maps well for all animals. The right column in</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="497" width="519">Figure 3 shows the daily animal activities by aggregating f temporally. These</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="515" width="346">curves match the animals diurnal patterns well, too.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="533" width="496">The Socioscope estimates are superior to the baseline methods in Table 1.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="551" width="519">Due to space limit we only present two examples on chipmunks, but note that</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="569" width="519">similar observations exist for all animals. The baseline estimator of simply scal-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="587" width="519">ing x(1)+ x(2) produced the temporal and spatial aggregates in Figure 5(a,b).</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="605" width="519">Compared to Figure 3(b, right), the temporal curve has a spurious peak around</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="622" width="519">4-5pm. The spatial map contains spurious intensity in California and Texas,</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="640" width="519">states outside the chipmunk range as shown in Figure 3(b, left). Both are pro-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="658" width="519">duced by population bias when and where there were strong background social</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="676" width="519">media activities (see Figure 2(b,c)). In addition, the spatial map contains 27</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="694" width="519">holes (states with zero intensity, colored in blue) due to data scarcity. In con-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="712" width="519">trast, Socioscopes estimates in Figure 3 avoid this problem by regularization.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="2" top="730" width="519">Another baseline estimator (x(1)+ x(2))/z(1) is shown in Figure 5(c). Although</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="748" width="519">corrected for population bias, this estimator lacks the transition model and reg-</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="766" width="339">ularization. It does not address data scarcity either.</text>
2 <text font="5" height="16" left="202" textpieces="1" top="808" width="144">6  Future Work</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="842" width="519">Using social media as a data source for spatio-temporal signal recovery is an</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="860" width="519">emerging area. Socioscope represents a rst step toward this goal. There are</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="878" width="141">many open questions:</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="896" width="496">1. We treated target posts as certain. In reality, a natural language processing</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="914" width="519">system can often supply a condence. For example, a tweet might be deemed to</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="932" width="519">be a target post only with probability 0.8. It will be interesting to study ways</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="950" width="333">to incorporate such condence into our framework.</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="225" textpieces="0" top="968" width="496">2. The temporal delay and spatial displacement between the target event and</text>
2 <text font="1" height="13" left="202" textpieces="0" top="986" width="519">the generation of a post is commonplace, as discussed in footnote 2. Estimating</text>
=============================== PAGE ===================================
